    "summary": "Assyria was a kingdom centered in the upper Tigris River valley of northern Mesopotamia, with its heartland around the ancient cities of Ashur, Nineveh, and Nimrud. The Assyrian state underwent several phases of expansion and contraction over more than a millennium, evolving from a trading city-state in the early second millennium BC into one of the most powerful empires of the ancient world.\n\nThe [[event:1830|Middle Assyrian Empire]] (c. 1392–1077 BC) marked the first phase of significant imperial expansion, as Assyrian kings extended control across northern Mesopotamia and competed with Mitanni and Babylon for regional dominance. King Tukulti-Ninurta I briefly captured Babylon around 1225 BC, a remarkable achievement recorded in an Assyrian epic. The Middle Assyrian period also produced a distinctive law code and administrative system. This phase of Assyrian power was disrupted by the broader [[event:1815|Bronze Age Collapse]] around 1200 BC.\n\nAssyria survived the Bronze Age Collapse in reduced form, and from the tenth century BC the state began rebuilding its power. The Neo-Assyrian Empire, emerging fully in the ninth century BC, would eventually become the first empire to exercise continuous control over a vast swath of the Near East. During the period covered by this era, Assyrian military organization, including professional armies, siege machinery, and cavalry, was developing into the formidable war machine that would dominate the Iron Age Near East.\n\nAssyrian culture was characterized by elaborate royal palace complexes adorned with carved stone reliefs depicting military campaigns, hunting scenes, and royal ceremonies. The Assyrian kings were prolific builders and patrons of scribal learning, accumulating libraries of clay tablets covering omens, ritual, mathematics, and history. Assyrian religion centered on the national god Ashur, whose interests the king was understood to advance through conquest and the maintenance of cosmic order.",
